<http://testwebsite/testProgram#Data-id_20260412200740_557-generated_answer>
    a <http://purl.dataone.org/provone/2015/01/15/ontology#Data> ;
    <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "generated_answer@en^^<xsd:string>" ;
    <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#value> """Before your workout, it's essential to eat foods that provide a quick energy boost while being mindful of your diabetes management. Since your diet preference is carnivorous, let's focus on protein-rich and low-carb options that are also easy on your blood sugar levels.

1. **Chicken or Turkey Breast**: Lean poultry is an excellent source of protein and can provide sustained energy. Consider having a small portion, like a grilled chicken/turkey slice, about an hour before your workout.

2. **Greek Yogurt with Berries**: While fruits are generally high in carbohydrates, a small handful of berries like blueberries combined with unsweetened Greek yogurt can provide an antioxidant boost and moderate carbs. The protein from the yogurt will help sustain energy.

3. **Hard-Boiled Eggs**: Eggs are a compact protein source. Consuming a couple of hard-boiled eggs can help keep your energy levels up without spiking your blood sugar.

4. **Nuts or Nut Butter**: Small amounts of nuts, like almonds or walnuts, or a spoonful of nut butter can provide healthy fats and protein. They're also convenient and easy to carry.

5. **Cheese Sticks or Slices**: Cheese is low in carbohydrates and a good protein source. Opt for low-fat cheese if you're concerned about saturated fats.

6. **Tuna Salad**: A small portion of tuna mixed with a bit of olive oil or mayonnaise can provide a good mix of protein and healthy fats. You can have it on a slice of cucumber or lettuce wrap.

7. **Beef Jerky**: Look for a low-sodium, low-sugar variety. It’s high in protein and can be an excellent pre-workout snack.

Remember to monitor your blood sugar levels before and after your workout to ensure they stay within your target range. Drink plenty of water to stay hydrated, especially during workouts. Adjust portions according to your specific energy needs and preferences. Always consult with your healthcare provider or a dietitian when making significant changes to your diet, especially with a condition like diabetes.@en^^<xsd:string>""" ;
    <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasGeneratedBy> <http://testwebsite/testProgram#id_20260412200740_99>, <http://testwebsite/testProgram#id_20260412200742_397> .

<http://testwebsite/testProgram#Data-id_20260412200740_707-user_prompt>
    a <http://purl.dataone.org/provone/2015/01/15/ontology#Data> ;
    <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "user_prompt@en^^<xsd:string>" ;
    <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#value> "I need suggestions for light and energy-boosting foods to eat before my gym workout.@en^^<xsd:string>" .

